Neovim editor-side half of steno-ts: watches insert mode for Plover-emitted sentinel-wrapped tokens like `@@STKWR-PBGS/TPH-FLT` and expands them into LSP snippets via `vim.snippet`. The compiler in this repo (src/snippet.ts) does all the real work — computing counts, appending types, numbering tabstops — and writes the result to `out/snippets.json`; this plugin only deletes the matched token text and calls `vim.snippet.expand(body)` with the corresponding precompiled body.

Requires Neovim 0.10+ (checks `vim.snippet` truthiness and silently no-ops if absent — no error is raised, so on older Neovim this plugin does nothing at all rather than failing loudly). `M.setup(opts)` must be called with `opts.snippets_path` pointing at `out/snippets.json`; if omitted, setup logs an error and aborts before installing any autocmds. `config.filetypes` defaults to the four JS/TS variants; passing an empty table disables filetype filtering entirely (attaches to `"*"`).

The sentinel `OPEN`/`CLOSE` constant `"@@"` must stay byte-identical to `SENTINEL_OPEN`/`SENTINEL_CLOSE` in `src/snippet.ts` — if the TS side changes the fence string, tokens will never match here. The comment there explains why: ASCII, non-auto-pairing, and never valid TS syntax, so it can't collide with real code the user is typing.

`token_before_cursor()` is the trickiest piece: it requires the line-prefix-up-to-cursor to end exactly with `CLOSE`, then strips that trailing close *before* searching for the last `OPEN`, specifically to avoid `OPEN` and `CLOSE` (both `"@@"`) matching the same substring when they're identical strings. It scans for the *last* occurrence of `OPEN` in the remaining prefix (not the first), so nested/malformed fences resolve to the innermost/last open. Returns `key, start_col` where `start_col` is a 0-indexed byte column, or `nil` if no complete token ends at the cursor.

`try_expand()` is wired to `TextChangedI` per-buffer (attached once per buffer via `attach_buffer`, gated by filetype), looks up the extracted key in the module-level `snippets` table (loaded once at setup from JSON via `vim.json.decode`), and if found deletes the token region with `nvim_buf_set_text` and calls `vim.snippet.expand`. If the key isn't in the snippets table (e.g., stale/missing json), it silently no-ops — no error surfaced to the user mid-typing.

`M._try_expand` and `M._token_before_cursor` are exposed only for manual/test invocation, not part of the normal runtime flow.